  "texts": [
    "Every full standard possibility frame satisfies Rcommon: if x ′ ⊑ x and x ′ R i y ′, then ∃z ⊑ y ′: x ′ R i z and xR i z.Proof.",
    "If x ′ ⊑ x and x ′ R i y ′, then by the R-rule property of full frames ( § 2.3), ∃y: xR i y ≬ y ′, so ∃z: z ⊑ y and z ⊑ y ′.",
    "Then since xR i y and x ′ R i y ′, we have xR i z and x ′ R i z by R-down for standard frames.",
    "Some of the first-order correspondents produced by Proposition 6.23 have even simpler forms over strong possibility frames (Definition 2.36), which we will note in the following example.Example 6.26 (Familiar Axioms).",
    "Consider the following special cases of the correspondence between ♢ α □ β p → □ δ ♢ γ p and∀x∀y xR δ y → ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀z(x ′ R α z → ∃u(yR γ u ∧ zR β u)),and between □ β p → □ δ ♢ γ p and ∀x∀y(xR δ y → ∃u(yR γ u ∧ xR β u)), over full standard frames from Proposition 6.23 (recall that if σ is empty, then xR σ y means y ⊑ x):• □ i p → ♢ i p corresponds to ∀x∀y(y ⊑ x → ∃u(yR i u ∧ xR i u)), which by Fact 6.25 is equivalent to seriality, ∀x ∃u xR i u.• ♢ i p → □ i p corresponds to ∀x∀y(xR i y → ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀z(x ′ R i z → ∃u(u ⊑ y ∧ u ⊑ z))), i.e., ∀x∀y(xR i y → ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀z(x ′ R i z → y ≬ z)).• □ i p → p corresponds to ∀x∀y ⊑ x ∃u ⊑ y xR i u, which by Fact 6.25 is equivalent to ∀x ∃u ⊑ x xR i u."
